ontaminants. In addition to the filter media, Typha latifolia and Phragmites australis were planted in the CW to provide surface area for biofilm formation and to facilitate phytoremediation. These plants were selected based on their well-established role in constructed wetlands for wastewater treatment. The system was operated for a 3–4 week acclimation period before introducing wastewater, allowing the plants to establish their root systems and facilitate microbial growth in the rhizosphere. Biochar was produced from sugarcane straw using a slow pyrolysis method at reaction temperatures of 400 °C, 600 °C, and 800 °C (Fig. 2), under oxygen-limited conditions. The pyrolysis temperature significantly influenced the biochar’s properties, with higher temperatures enhancing its surface area, porosity, and stability. Biochar was selected as a filter media in the constructed wetland due to these advantageous properties, such as its ability to absorb a large number of exchangeable cations, develop abundant oxygen functional groups on its surface, and exhibit a highly porous structure. These attributes make biochar particularly suitable for long-term applications in soil and water environments. Its rich and stable carbon content, combined with its strong adsorption capabilities and excellent structural stability, ensures effective contaminant removal and system durability in the constructed wetland context [7, 25].Fig. 2Preparation of Biochar material Preparation of Biochar material After establishing the plant and microbial communities in the CW, the system was fed with 14 L of domestic wastewater, which flowed through the wetland at a rate of 3.8 US gallons/day (approximately 14.4 L/day). The hydraulic retention time of the system is 0.25 days (6.07) hours calculated from the flow rate and volume of the system as shown in Eq. 1. This flow rate was selected to simulate real-world hydraulic loading conditions within the constraints of a lab-scale setup. It reflects typical 