## Introduction
The global challenge of water pollution, particularly through the discharge of contaminants from domestic and industrial wastewater, poses significant risks to ecosystems, public health, and the environment [28]. As the world’s population continues to rise, the demand for clean water increases, exacerbating water scarcity issues. In 2014, 54% of the global population lived in urban areas, with household water usage representing approximately 11% of total water consumption [13]. By 2025, over 100 countries are expected to experience varying degrees of water scarcity, highlighting the urgent need for sustainable water management solutions, including efficient wastewater treatment technologies [23]. Despite the growing reliance on wastewater for addressing water shortages, conventional wastewater treatment methods often fail to effectively remove contaminants, resulting in the persistence of pollutants such as antibiotic-resistant bacteria (ARB) and antibiotic-resistant genes (ARGs), which can be transferred to humans and other organisms [40]. The overuse of antibiotics in human healthcare and animal farming has led to the rise of ARB and ARGs, which are increasingly detected in wastewater effluents. These resistant microorganisms pose a serious threat to public health, as they complicate the treatment of infections and contribute to the spread of resistance across environments [33, 34]. Conventional wastewater treatment plants are often not equipped to remove ARB effectively, which has driven the search for innovative approaches to mitigate this growing problem. Among these, constructed wetlands (CWs), particularly those integrated with natural systems, have shown promise in removing a wide range of pollutants, including emerging organic contaminants (EOCs), as well as reducing ARB and ARGs. However, many studies have primarily focused on the removal of conventional pollutants, with limited attention given to the combined removal of both physicochemical parameters and ARB [24]. The use of biochar as a substrate material in CWs is a novel approach that has gained attention due to its ability to enhance microbial activity, improve nutrient and oxygen flow, and promote plant growth [22]. Biochar, a carbon-rich material produced from the pyrolysis of organic biomass, has been shown to support diverse microbial communities, which are essential for pollutant degradation. When used as a substrate in CWs, biochar can improve the system’s ability to treat wastewater by increasing the efficiency of both nutrient removal and the attenuation of contaminants such as ARB. The potential of biochar-amended CWs to outperform traditional wastewater treatment systems in removing ARB, antibiotics, and ARGs is increasingly recognized [29]. Despite this growing interest, there remains a need to explore and optimize the use of biochar, particularly in systems designed to treat domestic wastewater contaminated with ARB. Antibiotic-resistant bacteria, especially those producing extended-spectrum β-lactamases (ESBLs), represent one of the most critical challenges in modern medicine. These enzymes, which can degrade β-lactam antibiotics, such as cephalosporins, penicillin, and monobactams, contribute to the widespread resistance among both Gram-negative and some Gram-positive bacteria [2]. The presence of ESBL-producing bacteria in wastewater effluents is particularly concerning because these bacteria are resistant to multiple classes of antibiotics, complicating treatment options for infections. The ability of CWs, particularly those amended with biochar, to mitigate the presence of ESBL-producing ARB and reduce the spread of ARGs in wastewater is an area of increasing importance. While some studies have shown success in removing these bacteria from wastewater, the integration of biochar with CWs in the context of ARB and ARGs remains under-explored and warrants further investigation. This study seeks to address critical gaps in the understanding and application of CWs for removing antibiotic-resistant bacteria from domestic wastewater. Specifically, the objectives are:Evaluate the efficiency of biochar-amended CWs in improving physicochemical parameters, such as chemical oxygen demand (COD), biological oxygen demand (BOD), nitrogen and sulfate.Evaluate the efficiency of biochar-amended CW in reducing Antibiotic resistance bacteria.Furthermore, the study will assess the multidrug resistance (MDR) profiles of ARB isolates before and after treatment and analyze the presence of resistance genes, particularly blaTEM and blaCTX-M. Evaluate the efficiency of biochar-amended CWs in improving physicochemical parameters, such as chemical oxygen demand (COD), biological oxygen demand (BOD), nitrogen and sulfate. Evaluate the efficiency of biochar-amended CW in reducing Antibiotic resistance bacteria. Furthermore, the study will assess the multidrug resistance (MDR) profiles of ARB isolates before and after treatment and analyze the presence of resistance genes, particularly blaTEM and blaCTX-M. By investigating the novel combination of biochar and CWs for wastewater treatment, this research aims to contribute to the development of more effective, sustainable and cost-efficient solutions to address the global challenge of antibiotic resistance in wastewater management.

