## Description of study site and system design
The wastewater used in this study was sourced from the D-type colony of Quaid-i-Azam University, Islamabad, Pakistan, and transported to the experimental site for treatment. A lab-scale constructed wetland (CW) system was selected for the study to ensure controlled conditions. The system (Fig. 1) was operated in a greenhouse protected from rainfall. The site (outside Microbiology department QAU Islamabad) was selected to receive no precipitation but the maximum light intensity. The system was operated under varying temperature ranges from 18 °C to 35 °C due to seasonal temperature variations from April to June. The system was designed using parameters from the K-C Model [20] for horizontal subsurface flow (HSSF) wetlands, which accounts for factors like flow rate, influent concentration, and removal efficiency.Fig. 1Schematic design and construction of horizontal lab-scale constructed wetland Schematic design and construction of horizontal lab-scale constructed wetland

## Calculation of CW area
The area of the CW cell was determined using the K-C Model (Eq. 1), which is widely employed for sizing constructed wetlands for wastewater treatment. The equation considers key factors such as the flow rate (Q), influent and effluent concentrations, and a model-specific constant (KA). The equation used in this study is as follows:1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
