				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Area=\left(\frac{0.0365Q}{{K}_{A}}\right)ln\left(\frac{{C}_{i}-{C}^{*}}{{C}_{e}-{C}^{*}}\right)$$\end{document}Area=0.0365QKAlnCi-C∗Ce-C∗where:Q is the flow rate (m3/day),Ci and Ce are the influent and effluent concentrations (mg/L),C* is the target concentration (mg/L),KA is a site-specific constant. Q is the flow rate (m3/day), Ci and Ce are the influent and effluent concentrations (mg/L), C* is the target concentration (mg/L), KA is a site-specific constant. The CW area was calculated based on the parameters established in a recent study [36], which validated the effectiveness of this sizing approach for similar wastewater treatment scenarios. This calculation ensured that the system was appropriately scaled to achieve the desired treatment efficiencies, aligning with the specific wastewater characteristics and treatment objectives.

## Experimental setup
The lab-scale constructed wetland system consists of three interconnected compartments designed for treating domestic wastewater. A schematic of the system is shown in Fig. 1. The entire setup spans 11 feet horizontally from the inlet to the outlet, with a vertical depth of 4.5 feet in the first compartment. The system includes two horizontal subsurface flow (HSSF) compartments, each of which is optimized with specific filter media to maximize treatment efficiency. In this study, biochar derived from sugarcane bagasse was used as a non-traditional filter media instead of conventional materials such as gravel or sand. Biochar was prepared using a slow pyrolysis method under anaerobic conditions at three different temperatures: 400 °C, 600 °C, and 800 °C. The first two compartments of the CW were filled with a base layer of 1-inch gravel, followed by 2 inches of biochar and 2 inches of sand at the top. These media were chosen due to their beneficial properties, such as biochar’s high porosity, surface area, and adsorption capacity, which enhance wastewater treatment through physical and chemical interactions with contaminants. In addition to the filter media, Typha latifolia and Phragmites australis were planted in the CW to provide surface area for biofilm formation and to facilitate phytoremediation. These plants were selected based on their well-established role in constructed wetlands for wastewater treatment. The system was operated for a 3–4 week acclimation period before introducing wastewater, allowing the plants to establish their root systems and facilitate microbial growth in the rhizosphere.

## Biochar preparation
Biochar was produced from sugarcane straw using a slow pyrolysis method at reaction temperatures of 400 °C, 600 °C, and 800 °C (Fig. 2), under oxygen-limited conditions. The pyrolysis temperature significantly influenced the biochar’s properties, with higher temperatures enhancing its surface area, porosity, and stability. Biochar was selected as a filter media in the constructed wetland due to these advantageous properties, such as its ability to absorb a large number of exchangeable cations, develop abundant oxygen functional groups on its surface, and exhibit a highly porous structure. These attributes make biochar particularly suitable for long-term applications in soil and water environments. Its rich and stable carbon content, combined with its strong adsorption capabilities and excellent structural stability, ensures effective contaminant removal and system durability in the constructed wetland context [7, 25].Fig. 2Preparation of Biochar material Preparation of Biochar material

## System operation
After establishing the plant and microbial communities in the CW, the system was fed with 14 L of domestic wastewater, which flowed through the wetland at a rate of 3.8 US gallons/day (approximately 14.4 L/day). The hydraulic retention time of the system is 0.25 days (6.07) hours calculated from the flow rate and volume of the system as shown in Eq. 1. This flow rate was selected to simulate real-world hydraulic loading conditions within the constraints of a lab-scale setup. It reflects typical domestic wastewater flow rates while ensuring that the hydraulic retention time was adequate for effective treatment within the limited spatial and operational dimensions of the constructed wetland. Additionally, this flow rate aligns with established guidelines and methodologies from previous studies on small-scale constructed wetlands [21], providing a reliable basis for comparison.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
