## Physicochemical properties
A range of physicochemical parameters were analyzed to evaluate the treatment efficiency of the constructed wetland. These included:pH: Measured using a Sartorius pH meter.Electrical conductivity (EC), salinity, and total dissolved solids (TDS): Measured using a Multi-parameter PCSTestrTM 35.Chemical oxygen demand (COD) and biological oxygen demand (BOD): Determined using standard kit methods (MERCK, 2023).Dissolved oxygen (DO): Measured with a CRISON OXI 45 + digital DO meter.Total nitrogen (TN) and total sulfate content (SO₄2⁻): Measured using standard laboratory methods. pH: Measured using a Sartorius pH meter. Electrical conductivity (EC), salinity, and total dissolved solids (TDS): Measured using a Multi-parameter PCSTestrTM 35. Chemical oxygen demand (COD) and biological oxygen demand (BOD): Determined using standard kit methods (MERCK, 2023). Dissolved oxygen (DO): Measured with a CRISON OXI 45 + digital DO meter. Total nitrogen (TN) and total sulfate content (SO₄2⁻): Measured using standard laboratory methods. The analytical methods followed standard protocols (• APHA [1]) to ensure accurate and reliable results.

## Normal and resistant CFU count
The microbial populations, including common sewage bacteria such as Salmonella, Shigella, Escherichia coli, and Streptococcus, were enumerated using the serial dilution and plate count method on Nutrient Agar. For testing antibiotic resistance, the media was supplemented with antibiotics ciprofloxacin, cefixime, and linezolid. The colony-forming units (CFU) were counted using a digital colony counter.

## Antimicrobial susceptibility testing (AST)
The modified Kirby-Bauer disk diffusion method [41] was used to assess the antimicrobial resistance of isolated bacteria. The antibiotics tested included ciprofloxacin, ceftriaxone, chloramphenicol, cefotaxime, and doxycycline. The zones of inhibition were measured after 24 h of incubation at 37 °C.

## Molecular identification
Genomic DNA of multi-drug resistant (MDR) isolates was extracted using the boiling method [8]. PCR amplification was performed using Techne® Prime thermocycler, followed by gel electrophoresis to analyze the presence of resistance genes. The sequences of the primers used are provided in Table 4.

## Characterization of the microbial community in the rhizosphere
The microbial community in the rhizosphere was analyzed by culturing bacteria from the gravel and macrophyte roots. Serial dilutions were plated on selective media (e.g., Mannitol Salt Agar, MacConkey Agar, Eosin Methylene Blue Agar), followed by incubation at 37 °C for 24 h. The colonies were then isolated and identified based on morphology, biochemical tests, and Gram staining.

## Statistical analysis
The data obtained from the physicochemical and microbiological analyses were statistically analyzed using SPSS Statistics 23.0. Descriptive statistics such as means and standard deviations were calculated. One-way ANOVA, paired-samples t-test, and unpaired-samples t-test were used to assess the significance of differences between treatment groups, with a significance level of p < 0.05. Graphs were constructed using Microsoft Excel.

## Results
