## Discussion
In the current study, biochar was used as an amendment medium along with the conventional filter media, i.e., gravel and sand, in constructed wetlands (CWs). This approach aimed to address challenges related to wastewater treatment, including pollutant removal efficiency, antibiotic resistance, and scalability for real-world applications. Compared to traditional CW systems, the addition of biochar introduces a novel enhancement due to its adsorption properties and microbial habitat potential, making it highly relevant to the ongoing quest for sustainable wastewater treatment technologies. The study’s novelty lies in using biochar produced at varied pyrolysis temperatures (400 °C, 600 °C, and 800 °C) to optimize pollutant removal efficiencies. Previous studies have highlighted the varied responses of biochar to pollutant adsorption based on pyrolysis temperatures [6]. For instance, biochar produced at 400 °C retains higher nitrogen and oxygen content, enhancing adsorption for specific ions and pollutants, while higher temperatures (500 °C to 700 °C) improve surface area and carbon content [3, 17]. However, temperatures beyond 800 °C may reduce adsorption capacity due to structural changes limiting ion-exchange functional groups [31]. By employing a combination of biochar varieties, this study ensures a balance between physical adsorption, chemical adsorption, and microbial habitat formation, offering a holistic approach. The current lab scale CWs showed a significant reduction in the levels of COD, DO, BOD, total nitrogen, and sulfate content. In the current study initially, after optimization of the CW, the percent reduction of the above-mentioned parameters was found to be insignificant but after four weeks, when the values for these parameters were again determined, a prominent percent reduction was observed in all parameters. Biochar-amended CWs showed a reduction in COD from 7 to 57% after 12 weeks of completion of cycles, while the percent reduction for DO and BOD were determined to be 7% to 54% and 57% to 81%, respectively. Similarly, the sulfate content and TN reduced from 14 to 77% and 52% to 71%, respectively. The TDS and EC were reduced from 37 to 53% and 4% to 45%, respectively. Several investigations have demonstrated the excellent COD, TN, and TP removal efficiencies of biochar. According to [38] the removal efficiencies in the baffled wetland with biochar were all > 70% when the influent concentrations of COD, NH+4 -N, and TP were 244–336 mg/L, 37.5–59.1 mg/L, and 3.0–5.9 mg/L, respectively. Both chemical and physical adsorption were used to adsorb N and P via biochar. The structure and surface area of biochar was linked to physical adsorption, while the kind of biochar and the quantity and kind of functional groups were associated to chemical adsorption [42]. The mechanisms involved in nitrogen removal in CWs include volatilization, ammonification, nitrification/denitrification, plant uptake, and matrix adsorption. Moreover, multiple studies have shown the capability of biochar to remove nitrogen [16]. Electrical conductivity (EC) measures how many dissolved substances, chemicals, and minerals are in the water. Measurements of electrical conductivity are used by wastewater treatment plants to determine which treatment method will remove pollutants and impurities efficiently. Previous studies have reported EC, and TDS for untreated sewage water to be 410 µS/cm and 480 mg/L, respectively [32]. In particular, when it comes to lowering electrical conductivity (EC) during wastewater treatment, biochar has shown a promising material to improve the effectiveness of constructed wetlands. Due to its high porosity, huge surface area, and adsorption capabilities, it is good at capturing ions and salts that have been dissolved [14]. While the values for organic pollutants i.e., BOD and COD are interrelated with the amount of DO. As dissolved oxygen reflects the biological and physical processes prevailing in the water bodies and is considered an important parameter in water quality assessment [19]. Biochar, a carbon-rich material with a highly porous structure, enhances the adsorption of organic pollutants and serves as a habitat for microorganisms essential for degrading organic matter. It not only captures contaminants but also retains nutrients, promoting both pollutant removal and vegetation growth in the wetland ecosystem. These properties enable biochar to effectively capture COD and BOD from wastewater [27, 30, 43]. Studies indicate that CWs amended with biochar can achieve COD removal rates as high as 91.3% and BOD removal rates around 93% under optimal conditions [16]. The results we obtained of COD (87.6%), BOD (91.3%) is consistent with the results obtained by Zhang, who recorded 89% BOD and 85% COD removal in similarly designed wetlands. Moreover, More than 70% removal efficiency benchmark highlighted in the review by Vymazal [37], indicating the system’s potential for high-nutrient load applications Vymazal [37, 44]. Seasonal variations significantly influenced treatment performance. Warmer temperatures in summer enhanced microbial activity, leading to higher removal efficiencies for BOD, COD, and nitrogen. Conversely, lower winter temperatures reduced metabolic rates, slightly lowering treatment performance. pH remained relatively stable, though slight acidification during winter was noted. Besides the determination of these physiochemical parameters, the untreated and treated sewage water samples were analyzed by using conventional serial dilution method to observe the percentage of resistant CFU reduction of common sewage bacteria for example Salmonella, Shigella, E. coli, Streptococcus etc. A study reported that due to the high concentrations of coliforms and E. coli, the water’s microbiological quality fails to meet the requirements of current Brazilian law, rendering it unfit even for recreational activities like bathing and leisure [5]. In the current study, antibiotic resistant microorganisms were isolated against linezolid, ciprofloxacin and cefixime and identified. CWs proved to be very efficient with the reduction rates of resistant strains reaching up to 99% and above against linezolid, ciprofloxacin, and cefixime in water samples of influent and effluent. The MDR strains isolated from influent and effluent were confirmed based on the AST against selected antibiotics. In 2018, the World Health Organization (WHO), stated that the advent of numerous drug-resistant bacteria poses a possible risk to health. Methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA), vancomycin-resistant Enterococcus (VRE), multi- drug resistant Mycobacterium tuberculosis (MDR TB), and carbapenem-resistant Enterobacteriaceae (CRE) gut bacteria are just a few examples of multi-drug resistant organisms that cause serious diseases such as toxic shock syndrome, pneumonia, endocarditis and skin infections; therefore, they must be treated. Five antibiotics from different classes—ciprofloxacin, ceftriaxone, chloramphenicol, cefotaxime, and doxycycline—were selected to test their efficacy against organisms that were resistant to ciprofloxacin, cefixime, and linezolid. Various isolates were found to be MDR against the selected antibiotics. Five and six isolates, which were previously isolated against linezolid and ciprofloxacin respectively, were found to be MDR by testing against the afore-mentioned antibiotics. No MDR strains were found among those isolated from cefixime-resistant strains. The CW has been reported with efficient removal efficiencies of 7.1 log for total coliforms and 5.1 log for fecal coliforms, highlighting the system’s efficiency in wastewater treatment [4]. Ibekwe et al. [18] reported tetracycline (195 isolates, 46.3%), ampicillin (88 isolates, 20.9%), erythromycin (85 isolates, 20.2%), streptomycin (77 isolates, 18.3%), and sulfisoxazole (69 isolates, 16.4%) were the antimicrobials most frequently associated with MDR [18]. Based on the 