## Limitations
Biochar Longevity: Biochar helps remove pollutants, but over time, it may break down and lose effectiveness. This means it might need to be replaced or refreshed regularly.Scalability: What works well in small lab experiments might not work the same way in large real-world systems. Keeping biochar quality consistent and dealing with different types of wastewater can be challenging [26].Potential Clogging: Since biochar has a fine structure, it could block water flow in constructed wetlands. To prevent this, we can adjust the water flow time or mix biochar with larger materials to improve drainage [11]. Biochar Longevity: Biochar helps remove pollutants, but over time, it may break down and lose effectiveness. This means it might need to be replaced or refreshed regularly. Scalability: What works well in small lab experiments might not work the same way in large real-world systems. Keeping biochar quality consistent and dealing with different types of wastewater can be challenging [26]. Potential Clogging: Since biochar has a fine structure, it could block water flow in constructed wetlands. To prevent this, we can adjust the water flow time or mix biochar with larger materials to improve drainage [11]. Accumulation of suspended solids and biofilm growth especially in the filter media’s upper layers leads to clogging due to long-term operation. Surface scraping and vegetation management, is essential to sustain hydraulic conductivity as a regular maintenance. Biofilm development, not only remove pollutant but also reduce porosity if unmanaged, eventually impacting oxygen transfer and nitrification. Scheduled maintenance and intermittent drying phases can overcome these effects.

