## Conclusions
This study demonstrated the efficiency of biochar-amended constructed wetlands in treating domestic wastewater by reducing various physicochemical and microbiological parameters. Biochar produced at different temperatures (400 °C, 600 °C, and 800 °C) was used to enhance removal efficiency, with varying results based on temperature. The wetland system showed substantial reductions in COD, BOD, DO, total nitrogen, sulfate, TDS, and EC after an optimization period, achieving maximum reductions of 57% for COD, 81% for BOD, and 77% for sulfate. Additionally, the study showed that the system is effective in reducing antibiotic-resistant bacteria (ARB) and genes (ARGs), specifically 99% reduction rates observed for multi-drug resistant strains. Biochar's properties of pollutant adsorption and nutrient retention due to its porous structure and ability to support microbial activity contributed significantly to making it a promising material for improving wetland performance. Further research is needed to asses field-scale implementation, possible environmental trade-offs and long-term performance as these results highlight the potential benefits of biochar-amended constructed wetlands.

## Future recommendations
To enhance nitrogen and phosphorous removal horizontal flow wetlands should integrate with vertical flow or anaerobic digesters in future work. Scaling up to industrial levels could involve modular HF-CW designs with automation for hydraulic loading control. Further studies focusing on long-term sustainability, cost-effectiveness, and microbial dynamics will aid in optimizing system design for real-world deployment.

